                                                                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="14468413" author="guillaume" created="Fri, 11 Dec 2009 08:52:20 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Ah, I expected Jason to assign the issue to himself, but Roshan beats him to it &lt;img class=&quot;emoticon&quot; src=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/images/icons/emoticons/wink.png&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot; align=&quot;absmiddle&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;
The idea would be to do more or less like what was done in the File variant of the constructor.&lt;br/&gt;
Basically, DGM#getText, taking of encodings if we have some encoding specified.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14468351" author="roshandawrani" created="Fri, 11 Dec 2009 08:59:35 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Guillaume, I saw that Jason had reported 2 issues today but assigned only &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/GROOVY-3935&quot; title=&quot;Update groovysh to use jansi for windows ANSI support&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;GROOVY-3935&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;GROOVY-3935&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt; to himself, so I took &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/GROOVY-3934&quot; title=&quot;GroovyCodeSource(URL) is not setting scriptText&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;GROOVY-3934&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;GROOVY-3934&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt; to be available &lt;img class=&quot;emoticon&quot; src=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/images/icons/emoticons/smile.png&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot; align=&quot;absmiddle&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Currently there is no GroovyCodeSource(URL, String encoding). There is only GroovyCodeSource(URL), so I made it same as GroovyCodeSource(File), i.e., with default encoding and was running the test suite locally.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Do you want me to introduce GroovyCodeSource(URL, String encoding) as well?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14468332" author="guillaume" created="Fri, 11 Dec 2009 09:08:48 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Why not, we could introduce it.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Something I&apos;ve been looking at also is that we may possibly guess the encoding thanks to the getContentEncoding() method on URLCionnection.&lt;br/&gt;
So in the constructor not taking an encoding, you could first check whether the encoding is specified through URLConnection#getContentEncoding().&lt;br/&gt;
If not, use the same technique as in the File variant.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14468371" author="roshandawrani" created="Fri, 11 Dec 2009 09:13:43 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Ok. So I will introduce GroovyCodeSource(URL, String encoding) for explicitly specified encoding, and change GroovyCodeSource(URL) to try to use URLConnection#getContentEncoding(), else fallback on default encoding.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14468284" author="roshandawrani" created="Fri, 11 Dec 2009 09:26:16 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Guillaume, is GroovyCodeSource(URL, String encoding) really needed?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Or, is it just sufficient to have GroovyCodeSource(URL) and first try to use URLConnection#getContentEncoding(), else fallback on default encoding.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14468383" author="guillaume" created="Fri, 11 Dec 2009 09:40:15 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;When someone really wants to specify an encoding, he&apos;d better use the reader variant, by providing a reader (appropriately configured to use the encoding he decides to use) on top of the URL connection he would have open.&lt;br/&gt;
So the constructor is not strictly needed at all, since there&apos;s anyway a way of specifying it through a different path.&lt;br/&gt;
I&apos;m not necessarily in favour of multiplying the constructors with all the possible variants, so it&apos;s okay not to add it, IMHO, since it&apos;s not strictly required.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So the GCS(URL) can just do as you say, try to use the content encoding if specified, otherwise, fallback on the default encoding.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14468403" author="roshandawrani" created="Fri, 11 Dec 2009 12:51:21 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Fixed&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
